 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-g1ud","title":"JUnit XML Test Reports for CI Integration","description":"# JUnit XML Test Reports for CI Integration

## What
Generate JUnit XML test reports for CI dashboards (GitHub Actions, Jenkins, etc.)
that provide:
- Per-test pass/fail status
- Timing information
- Failure details with stack traces
- Test suite grouping

## Why
CI systems need structured test output to:
- Display test results in PR checks
- Track test flakiness over time
- Send notifications on failures
- Generate trend reports

## Technical Design

### Using cargo-nextest
`cargo-nextest` is a modern test runner that provides JUnit XML output natively.

```bash
# Install
cargo install cargo-nextest

# Run tests with JUnit output
cargo nextest run --profile ci
```

### Nextest Configuration
```toml
# .config/nextest.toml

[profile.default]
# Default profile for local development
fail-fast = true
retries = 0

[profile.ci]
# CI profile with JUnit output
fail-fast = false
retries = 2
slow-timeout = { period = "60s", terminate-after = 2 }

[profile.ci.junit]
path = "target/nextest/ci/junit.xml"
report-time = true

# Store failure output
store-success-output = false
store-failure-output = true
```

### GitHub Actions Integration
```yaml
# .github/workflows/test.yml
name: Tests

on: [push, pull_request]

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Install Rust
        uses: dtolnay/rust-action@stable

      - name: Install nextest
        uses: taiki-e/install-action@nextest

      - name: Run tests
        run: cargo nextest run --profile ci

      - name: Upload test results
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        if: always()
        with:
          name: test-results
          path: target/nextest/ci/junit.xml

      - name: Test Report
        uses: dorny/test-reporter@v1
        if: always()
        with:
          name: Cargo Tests
          path: target/nextest/ci/junit.xml
          reporter: java-junit
```

### Test Summary Script
```bash
#\!/usr/bin/env bash
# scripts/test-summary.sh
# Parse JUnit XML and print summary

JUNIT_FILE=${1:-"target/nextest/ci/junit.xml"}

if [[ \! -f "$JUNIT_FILE" ]]; then
    echo "JUnit file not found: $JUNIT_FILE"
    exit 1
fi

# Extract counts using xmlstarlet
tests=$(xmlstarlet sel -t -v "//testsuite/@tests" "$JUNIT_FILE" 2>/dev/null | awk '{s+=$1}END{print s}')
failures=$(xmlstarlet sel -t -v "//testsuite/@failures" "$JUNIT_FILE" 2>/dev/null | awk '{s+=$1}END{print s}')
errors=$(xmlstarlet sel -t -v "//testsuite/@errors" "$JUNIT_FILE" 2>/dev/null | awk '{s+=$1}END{print s}')
time=$(xmlstarlet sel -t -v "//testsuite/@time" "$JUNIT_FILE" 2>/dev/null | awk '{s+=$1}END{printf "%.2f", s}')

echo "==============================================="
echo "                TEST SUMMARY                   "
echo "==============================================="
echo "Total tests:  $tests"
echo "Passed:       $((tests - failures - errors))"
echo "Failed:       $failures"
echo "Errors:       $errors"
echo "Time:         ${time}s"
echo "==============================================="

if [[ $failures -gt 0 ]] || [[ $errors -gt 0 ]]; then
    echo ""
    echo "FAILED TESTS:"
    xmlstarlet sel -t -m "//testcase[failure|error]" -v "@name" -n "$JUNIT_FILE"
    exit 1
fi

echo "✓ All tests passed\!"
```

### Nextest Filter Configuration
```toml
# .config/nextest.toml (continued)

[test-groups]
# Group tests for reporting
integration = { max-threads = 1, slow-timeout = { period = "120s" } }
unit = { max-threads = "num-cpus" }

[[profile.ci.overrides]]
filter = "test(e2e_)"
test-group = "integration"

[[profile.ci.overrides]]
filter = "not test(e2e_)"
